An approach towards explaining this phenomenon can be taken via the route of different growth paths. For stoichiometric dual-source PVD, MAPbI3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_3$$\end{document} follows Volmer–Weber island growth, resulting in randomly oriented small grains with sizes below 100 nm60. Typically, Volmer–Weber growth occurs when the cohesion energy between molecules of the deposited material is greater than the adhesion energy between the material and the sample60. In this case, agglomerations of the deposited material grow in vertical direction from the sample surface, while the surface-coverage advances slowly. When the adhesion energy is larger, layer-by-layer (Frank–van der Merwe) growth is expected, in which case the considered surface is covered quickly. This could be the case for PbI2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
